+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01VobmjgUHT7rvvdmCQEx76p","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"OK so \"close WebSocket for non-existent document\" passes (which means WS upgrade works), but the others fail on `waitForMessage`. That means the WebSocket connects (open fires) but the message never arrives.\n\nWait - the \"non-existent\" test doesn't use `connectWs`. It uses `new WebSocket(...)` directly. Let me check if `connectWs` is the problem. No, `connectWs` just wraps the same thing and resolves on 'open'. The message should come immediately after open because `handleConnection` sends sync right away.\n\nWait... is it possible that the issue is that the test runs in the second describe block's `beforeAll`, and by that time, the first describe block's server has been stopped via `afterAll`? No, they're separate instances.\n\nLet me check: the minimal test worked. The only difference is... let me look at the minimal test again:\n\nThe minimal test uses `beforeAll`/`afterAll` with a single instance. The server test also uses `beforeAll`/`afterAll`. But the minimal test file has only one describe block, whereas server.test.ts has two describe blocks, each with their own server.\n\nWait, could there be a conflict? Both describe blocks are in the same file. They run sequentially. The first block (REST API) starts a server and stops it. Then the second block (WebSocket Collaboration) starts another server on a different port. But maybe the first afterAll hasn't completed yet when the second beforeAll runs? No, vitest handles that correctly.\n\nLet me actually check if the WebSocket open event fires in the failing tests:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1187,"cache_read_input_tokens":71250,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1187},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_avai