+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_013mqEeRVbRX1iJb3QF2bRfE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Hmm, one thought: the \"non-existent\" test works because it sends a message AND closes. Maybe the close event is what flushes it. But that shouldn't be the case for normal sends.\n\nWait - actually let me re-examine. The test output says:\n1. WS connected, readyState=1\n2. But then the message never arrives\n\nBut in the non-existent test, `ws.on('open', ...)` fires and then `ws.on('message', ...)` fires. So the message DOES arrive.\n\nCould the issue be that the `handleUpgrade` callback is called and I send the sync message, but the message is sent before the client's `open` event fires? The `open` event on the client side might fire after the upgrade response is received but before any data frames are processed. If `ws.once('message', ...)` is only registered after the `connectWs` promise resolves (after `open` fires), the sync message might already have been received and buffered, but the event was emitted synchronously before the handler was registered.\n\nThat's it! The problem is a race condition:\n1. `handleUpgrade` completes, server calls `handleConnection` which calls `ws.send(sync)`\n2. Client receives the upgrade response -> fires `open` event -> `connectWs` resolves\n3. Test calls `waitForMessage` which registers `ws.once('message', ...)`\n4. But the sync message data has already been received/processed BEFORE step 3\n\nIn the direct node test, this doesn't happen because the event loop works differently. But in vitest with its worker model, this race might manifest.\n\nThe fix: register the `message` handler BEFORE the `open` event, or use a different approach where we buffer messages.\n\nLet me change `connectWs` to return both the ws and first message:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":270,"cache_read_input_tokens":75325,"cac